---
// Turnstile interactive demo.
//
// Rather than a single form, this shows three scenarios side by side, each
// opening a dedicated mock login page (/turnstile/login?scenario=...) so
// the "is the visitor a bot?" outcome is visually obvious without touching
// DevTools:
//   - human       — production widget (or CF's "always passes" test key)
//   - interactive — CF's test key that forces the checkbox challenge
//   - blocked     — CF's test key that always fails, visibly, client-side
//
// The scenario only ever picks a sitekey server-side (functions/api/
// [[path]].ts) — the browser never supplies its own key or secret.
---

<div class="space-y-4">
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
    Turnstile's outcome depends on what its risk signals say about the
    visitor. Pick a scenario below to open a mock login page pre-wired to
    Cloudflare's public test keys for that outcome — each one shows what a
    real visitor would actually see.
  </p>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
    <div class="demo-panel safe">
      <h3>Trusted human</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
        Browser signals look normal. The challenge runs invisibly and the
        widget shows a green check almost immediately — no interaction
        needed.
      </p>
      <a href="/turnstile/login?scenario=human" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn-primary">
        Open as a human →
      </a>
    </div>

    <div class="demo-panel" style="border-top: 3px solid #d97706;">
      <h3 style="color: #b45309;">Suspicious visitor</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
        Turnstile isn't sure and presents an interactive checkbox challenge.
        Solve it and the widget still passes — login proceeds normally.
      </p>
      <a href="/turnstile/login?scenario=interactive" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn-primary">
        Open as suspicious →
      </a>
    </div>

    <div class="demo-panel danger">
      <h3>Confirmed bot</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
        Turnstile classifies the session as automated and never issues a
        token. The widget shows its own failure state and login stays
        disabled — nothing reaches the server.
      </p>
      <a href="/turnstile/login?scenario=blocked" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn-danger">
        Open as a bot →
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
